# Setup Work

Get an isolated worktree ready for a task and **change into it**, then hand back to you. By default that is where it stops — you continue in the same session, already inside the worktree. Pass `--go` to have it keep working autonomously, all the way to a draft, self-assigned PR.

Two hard guarantees:

- **Never two worktrees for one branch.** A mandatory `git worktree list --porcelain` check runs first; if the branch already has a worktree, you are dropped into the existing one instead of a duplicate being created.
- **PR review / existing branches never get a fresh branch.** Reviewing a PR or continuing an existing branch checks *that* branch out — it does not fork a new one.

## How to invoke

```
# Linear issues (most common — PLT and SEC prefixes)
/setup-work PLT-456
/setup-work https://linear.app/metr/issue/PLT-456/fix-auth-timeout

# Reviewing or iterating on a PR (also common)
/setup-work https://github.com/METR/hawk/pull/1234
/setup-work PR 1234
/setup-work review the auth-rewrite PR

# Existing branch or freeform
/setup-work some/feature-branch
/setup-work fix the authentication timeout bug

# Set up AND keep working through to a draft PR (autonomous)
/setup-work PLT-456 --go
```

## Worktree convention

All worktrees live at **`.worktrees/<name>`** under the repo root — the project-local, gitignored location the `superpowers:using-git-worktrees` skill uses as its fallback when there's no native worktree tool. The same location is used on both opencode (the common case here — no native tool) and Claude Code, so a worktree created by one is found and reused by the other. setup-work follows that convention but drives creation with `git worktree add` directly, so that:

- branch names stay clean (`PLT-456/fix-auth`, not a mangled `worktree-*` name) — which keeps `/pr-create`'s Linear-tag detection working, and
- an existing branch (PR review) can be checked out — the native create-mode can only ever make a *new* branch.

The session is then moved into the worktree with the **`EnterWorktree`** tool in path mode (`EnterWorktree({path: .worktrees/<name>})`) — the agent-callable equivalent of `/cd`. Run setup-work from the main checkout so path-mode can enter a `.worktrees/` worktree. (On opencode there's no such tool; the twin `setup-work` command there uses the `/cd` command from the vendored `opencode-dir` plugin instead.)

## Steps

### 1. Parse input and flags

- `--go` anywhere in the args → **autonomous mode** (see step 6). Strip it before interpreting the rest.
- Interpret the remaining input per the table to get: target **branch**, **base ref**, whether the branch is **existing** (PR/branch) or **new**, and an optional **linear-issue-id**.

| Input | Action |
|---|---|
| Linear ID (`PLT-456`, `SEC-89`) or Linear URL | `mcp__linear__get_ticket`. **New** branch `ISSUE-ID/slug-from-title`, base `origin/main`. |
| GitHub PR URL, `PR 1234`, or "review the X PR" | `gh pr view` → the PR's head branch. **Existing** branch — check it out, base `origin/<pr-branch>`. Link any Linear reference found in the PR title/body. |
| Branch name (slug or contains `/`) | **Existing** branch. Check Linear for an issue matching the slug prefix; link if found. |
| Free text describing work | Ask: create a Linear issue for this, or treat as a quick experiment (`quick/<slug>`)? Only create the issue on explicit confirmation. **New** branch. |
| Empty | Ask what to work on. |

### 2. Refuse setup-on-main

If the request describes editing the main checkout directly, decline: "I'll set up a worktree for this — the main checkout stays on its branch." A dirty working tree in the current checkout is fine; worktrees are independent.

### 3. Mandatory reuse check

`git fetch origin`, then `git worktree list --porcelain`. If a worktree already exists for the target branch → `EnterWorktree({path})` into it and skip to step 5. **Never create a second worktree for a branch that already has one.**

### 4. Create the worktree

Worktree dir: `.worktrees/<safe-name>` at the repo's main root (`<safe-name>` = the branch with `/` → `-`). Verify `.worktrees/` is gitignored (`git check-ignore`); if not, add it to `.gitignore` and commit that one change first.

- **New** branch: `git worktree add .worktrees/<safe-name> -b <branch> origin/main`
- **Existing** branch (PR / branch review): fetch it, then `git worktree add .worktrees/<safe-name> <branch>` (no `-b`)

Then `EnterWorktree({path: .worktrees/<safe-name>})` to move the session in.

### 5. Default: report and STOP

Print:

```
Worktree: <abs-path>   (you are now cd'd in)
Branch:   <branch>
Issue:    <PLT-456 if linked/created, else "none">
```

Then **stop**. You are already inside the worktree — pick up the work yourself, or re-run with `--go` to have me continue.

### 6. `--go`: work autonomously through to a draft PR

Only when `--go` was passed. After the cd, do the actual work end-to-end and stop at a **draft, self-assigned PR** (using `/pr-create` conventions): implement, verify, commit on the feature branch, push, open the draft PR with `--assignee @me`. Never merge. If you genuinely hit a point where you lack the context or a decision is the user's to make, stop and ask rather than guess.

## Hard rules

- Worktrees only — never create or switch a feature branch in the *main* checkout.
- Always run the `git worktree list --porcelain` reuse check before creating anything.
- One worktree per branch, ever.
- PR review / existing branch → check that branch out; never `-b` a new one.
- Never create a Linear issue without explicit user confirmation.
- Default stops right after the cd. Only `--go` continues, and only as far as a draft, self-assigned PR.
